	<HR>
	Purpose:<br>
	This assignment exercises the use of HTML structures, and JavaScript expressions &amp; intrinsic functions (Chapter 5, Reed)
	<HR>
	<P>
	Replicate as closely as possible (<i>reverse engineer</i>) the following Webpage:
	<a href="http://web.stcloudstate.edu/aanda/cs200/screenshots/hw1f10example.bmp">Assignment 1 Web page image</a>
	<P>
	    Please follow the following guidelines in your design:
	<ul>
	    <li> Use HTML comments at the top of your HTML source file identifying:</li>
	    <ul>
		<li>where the file is located (e.g. <tt>~/cs200999/assignments/hw1.html</tt>)</li> 
		<li>the author (<i>you</i>) </li> 
		<li>what the program does</li> 
		<li>when you created the file</li> 
		<li>when you last modified the file</li>
	    </ul>
	    <li>Note:</li>
	    <ul>
		<li>whether an item is centered.</li>
		<li>whether a text item is emphasized with some combination of
		<b>bold</b>, <u>underline</u>, <i>italics</i>, or <font color="red">color</font>.</li>
		<li>which type of list: bullet or ordinal.</li>
		<li>the <tt>title</tt> content.</li>
	    </ul>
	    <li>Ensure that your source code is indented to enhance readability.</li>
	    <li>Use appropriately descriptive identifier labels for your variables.</li>
	    <li>Save your work in your <tt>Assignment1</tt> folder/directory.</li>
	    <li>Carbon-14 Dating:</li>
	    <ul>
		<li>All <b>AGE</b>s in the table and in the <i>Interactive</i> section are to be computed in JavaScript using the
		    <a href="http://science.howstuffworks.com/carbon-142.htm">Carbon-14 dating formula</a>.</li>
		<li>Use a <u>prompt</u> to input the <i>Interactive</i> Carbon-14 ratio.</li>
		<li>No <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_number_(programming)#Unnamed_numerical_constants">magic numbers</a>:
		    Assign to <i>appropriately labeled</i> variables the literal numeric constants (e.g. 5700) used in the formula.</li>
		<li><u>Round</u> the ages to the <i>nearest</i> integer.</li>
		<li>For the required <tt>round()</tt> &amp; <tt>log()</tt> function <i>Math Object <u>Methods</u></i>, see
		    <a href="http://www.w3schools.com/jsref/jsref_obj_math.asp">this link</a>.</li>
	    </ul>
	</ul>
	<P>
	    <HR>
	After testing thoroughly, submit this file to its D2L Dropbox.<br>
	Also, submit a <u>screenshot</u> of your Webpage replicating the example Webpage.
